that he said, Roberto, I have good
news, the decision and the dilemma

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:06.110
of waiting to be rescued or
going for a rescue is over.

00:18:06.110 --> 00:18:08.920
If we don't get up
ourselves, we will be dead.

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:10.930
And from that on, I
learned that in life,

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:13.140
you shouldn't wait
for the helicopters.

00:18:13.140 --> 00:18:16.930
We had to go walking to
tell them the helicopters

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:22.620
where our friends were.

00:18:22.620 --> 00:18:28.050
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Very few people
who are in a plane crash survive,

00:18:28.050 --> 00:18:34.450 position:56%
much less survive the length of time
after and yet you have been back

00:18:34.450 --> 00:18:40.340
to the site six times, I mean
some people would have, you know,

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:43.310
never wanted to see it again and
you've taken your children back.

00:18:43.310 --> 00:18:44.610
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Yeah.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:45.910
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Why?

00:18:45.910 --> 00:18:47.850
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: It took me some
time, and I said, well I'm here.

00:18:47.850 --> 00:18:50.840
And then I saw the people
in the concentration camps,

00:18:50.840 --> 00:18:55.500
that they would go back to
the place we were and I have

00:18:55.500 --> 00:18:56.960
to overcome the suffering.

00:18:56.960 --> 00:19:01.970
And then when I was there with
my sons, I felt the survivor,

00:19:01.970 --> 00:19:04.340
the people that had died were
laughing at me and saying, hey,

00:19:04.340 --> 00:19:06.650
Roberto, what a belly
you have grown,

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:09.530
you look like an old man,
you don't have no shame.

00:19:09.530 --> 00:19:12.590
And I would tell them, yes,
but I have my sons here

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:14.080
that they want them to meet you.

00:19:14.080 --> 00:19:19.070
And then my daughter said, daddy,
this is a very sad place but has

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:22.050
such a tremendous energy
and it's true,

00:19:22.050 --> 00:19:24.830
it's a place that had
a very strong energy.

00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:26.130
Miracles happen there.

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:28.510 position:56%
I have seen New York lawyers crying.

00:19:28.510 --> 00:19:29.860
You think--

00:19:29.860 --> 00:19:31.900
[ Laughter ]

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:34.100
-- a lawyer can cry?

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:35.460
They were crying there.

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:37.510
[ Laughter ]

00:19:37.510 --> 00:19:39.010
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Why would you
take a New York lawyer there?

00:19:39.010 --> 00:19:40.310
[ Laughter ]

00:19:40.310 --> 00:19:42.420
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: He was there.

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:45.790
He went by himself.

00:19:45.790 --> 00:19:49.170
He went by himself.

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:52.390
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: OK.

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:55.900
What's-- so you became-- you were
a medical student at that time.

00:19:55.900 --> 00:19:57.200
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Yeah.

00:19:57.200 --> 00:19:59.970
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: And you became
a pediatric cardiologist.

00:19:59.970 --> 00:20:01.270
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Mm-hmm.

00:20:01.270 --> 00:20:04.040
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Why did
you decide on that route?

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:07.050
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Well, my father
was a professor in cardiology

00:20:07.050 --> 00:20:10.530
and I was doing cardiac
catheterization

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:14.550
and there was another physician
doing a newborn heart diseases

00:20:14.550 --> 00:20:17.480
and I was very attracted by these

00:20:17.480 --> 00:20:21.340
because in newborns are
wrongly assembled from life

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:23.830
and elder people have
rotten coronary arteries

00:20:23.830 --> 00:20:27.690
because they're small, they
are fat, all the things I do

00:20:27.690 --> 00:20:30.640
and this newborns, you
could change some part

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:33.040
of their heart and
they were set off.

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:36.230
So I thought that was a
great challenge at that time,

00:20:36.230 --> 00:20:38.570
the 3-dimension electrocardiography
came out,

00:20:38.570 --> 00:20:41.980
and I could see their hearts and I
could see the hearts in their wombs

00:20:41.980 --> 00:20:45.990
of the mother and this
kind of fascinated me.

00:20:45.990 --> 00:20:48.520 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Is there a
connection for you in what you chose

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:51.370
to do and what happened to you?

00:20:51.370 --> 00:20:55.670
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: I thought there
wasn't but apparently, the life

00:20:55.670 --> 00:21:01.950
and death line is something
I want to challenge.

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:03.250
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Interesting.

00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:08.000
Do you believe in-- I'm
asking you a deep question.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.160
Do you believe in fate
or do you believe

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:14.850
in chance or something in between?

00:21:14.850 --> 00:21:17.570
Why did some people
survived, why not others,

00:21:17.570 --> 00:21:21.580
why are some of your patients
surviving and not others?

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:22.880
What is your outlook?

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:25.370
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: I don't in
life, what matters are chances,

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:27.720
what matters are choices.

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:31.470
It's what you choose, not what
happens to you and I believe

00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:35.560 position:56%
that some parents made an incredible
effort to go and get their surgery

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:37.980
down abroad in the states
and their-- get their life.

00:21:37.980 --> 00:21:42.610 position:56%
And someone didn't have the money or
didn't have the strength to do that

00:21:42.610 --> 00:21:44.950
and their kids died in Uruguay.

00:21:44.950 --> 00:21:47.260
So we have our heart
foundation there in Uruguay

00:21:47.260 --> 00:21:50.300
which we are helping and
trying to race the level.

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:52.470
Probably in school,
we learned very soon

00:21:52.470 --> 00:21:55.550
when the Christian brothers
told that the in rugby,

00:21:55.550 --> 00:21:57.140
the referee is always right.

00:21:57.140 --> 00:22:01.460
And I said, that's unfair and he
told me, who told you life is fair?

00:22:01.460 --> 00:22:05.270
We must take life as it comes
and we must take these realities

00:22:05.270 --> 00:22:08.320
and handle them that way.

00:22:08.320 --> 00:22:11.120
Yeah, probably you're
right, it's fate.

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:12.420
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Do you think?

00:22:12.420 --> 00:22:14.950
I mean from here in your
answer, I get the sense

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:17.390
that what you're saying
is there are circumstances

00:22:17.390 --> 00:22:19.010
and then there are what
we do with circumstances.

00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:21.980
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Yeah, there's
a certain leverage that you can do

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:24.650
and while there's life,
there's hope.

00:22:24.650 --> 00:22:28.210
And this is something that the
society of the snow we used.

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:31.240
Where there's life is
hope and maybe tomorrow.

00:22:31.240 --> 00:22:34.720
Though things don't make sense
in this everyday life and we are

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:39.240
so powerful and we have the car and
see the CR condition is very bad

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:43.430
and I believe that all this matter
realism makes us spiritually

00:22:43.430 --> 00:22:44.730
very poor.

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:49.750 position:56%
This is-- separate us from spiritual
life, all this material burden

00:22:49.750 --> 00:22:55.130
which we are immersed and we
cannot see the real lights.

00:22:55.130 --> 00:23:01.890
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: And you called
the group the society of the snow?

00:23:01.890 --> 00:23:03.190
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: The
brothers of the Andes.

00:23:03.190 --> 00:23:04.490
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: The
brothers of the Andes.

00:23:04.490 --> 00:23:05.790
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Yeah.

00:23:05.790 --> 00:23:07.090
But we got very contaminated,
you know.

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:08.930
We came seeing what is
going to tell our society,

00:23:08.930 --> 00:23:12.390
what is going to tell the pope
and then oh guys, you're heroes.

00:23:12.390 --> 00:23:16.670
No, we are just dirty people
and no two months, no--

00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:18.630
washing each other,
eating each other.

00:23:18.630 --> 00:23:20.490
No, no, you're heroes,
you're heroes.

00:23:20.490 --> 00:23:22.750
Yeah, do you think
so, we are heroes.

00:23:22.750 --> 00:23:25.430
Oh yeah, maybe we are
the heroes of the Andes.

00:23:25.430 --> 00:23:27.490
But that's better hero
than you are hero.

00:23:27.490 --> 00:23:29.080
No, no, we are all heroes.

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:33.390
So it was completely contaminated
the story of us but the version

00:23:33.390 --> 00:23:36.460
of society, so I think
we just should keep pure

00:23:36.460 --> 00:23:39.600
when a man is fate
to death and to fate.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.630
And that real-- the tools

00:23:41.630 --> 00:23:44.580
of the Andes are the
things I want to transmit.

00:23:44.580 --> 00:23:48.270
What do you resource and
what you should learn in--

00:23:48.270 --> 00:23:52.750
and the force of life is not
how you do things but why.

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:54.170
The real force is why.

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:59.600
When you have a reason for doing
something then you will find how

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:00.900
to do it.

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:02.350
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Speaking of
how the world looks at this,

00:24:02.350 --> 00:24:06.620
so what do you think of the-- this
was originally made most famous

00:24:06.620 --> 00:24:10.650
by the book Alive and then the
movie that was made from it.

00:24:10.650 --> 00:24:14.520
What do you think of it?

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:15.820
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: At the
beginning, we're complaining

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:18.410
because the book didn't
transmit what were there.

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:21.640
And then we had to learn than a
book never transmits what happened.

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:24.620
And then what is the reality,
when you thought you were there,

00:24:24.620 --> 00:24:26.580
what your friend thought
was happening there

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:30.120
and then I realize this is
like the story of the Titanic

00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:33.720
that there are many windows to look
at it, there's a window version,

00:24:33.720 --> 00:24:37.220 position:56%
there's an author version, there's--
there are the many ways of looking

00:24:37.220 --> 00:24:41.700
to this human experiment
behavior that was our tragedy.

00:24:41.700 --> 00:24:45.500
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Did anything
pleased you about the book in movie

00:24:45.500 --> 00:24:50.660
or anything that made you
anything in particular or anything

00:24:50.660 --> 00:24:52.550
that make you particularly angry?

00:24:52.550 --> 00:24:55.130
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: No, I think
that everything adds to the story

00:24:55.130 --> 00:24:57.520
and gives you a sight
of what happened.

00:24:57.520 --> 00:24:59.940
I would the say the Disney
film is like a documentary

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:02.670
of the feelings we
had on the mountain.

00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:06.640
I would say that Piers Paul Read,
the book Alive is a documentary

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:10.980
of what happened, of the narration
of what happened and besides that,

00:25:10.980 --> 00:25:14.800
every new book has the chances
of getting all the results

00:25:14.800 --> 00:25:17.450
of previous books, you know.

00:25:17.450 --> 00:25:19.380
It's like an upgrade.

00:25:19.380 --> 00:25:22.350
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: What--
you also have--

00:25:22.350 --> 00:25:26.410
you also have a reunion every year.

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:27.710
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Yeah,
we have a gathering,

00:25:27.710 --> 00:25:31.500
the first one with the
girlfriends where we're like 32.

00:25:31.500 --> 00:25:35.140
And last year, we're 180 with
all the grandsons and everything

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:39.210
so the society of Andes
procreated very happily.

00:25:39.210 --> 00:25:41.050
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: I was going to
ask you how things have changed,

00:25:41.050 --> 00:25:47.000
where you sort of told me over
the years, have things mellowed

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:50.270
like in anything, your
attitudes toward what happened

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:53.350
or is it still fresh in your mind.

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:55.850
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Oh, I know that
your plane might crash any moment

00:25:55.850 --> 00:25:59.090
and then we should be more
thankful and that we receive

00:25:59.090 --> 00:26:01.770
from life are lots
more than what we need

00:26:01.770 --> 00:26:04.780
and we do lots less in what we can.

00:26:04.780 --> 00:26:07.830
And we don't know what
is really horrible.

00:26:07.830 --> 00:26:11.890
I mean for me, jail is
lot better than the Andes.

00:26:11.890 --> 00:26:14.110
While you're in jail, you
have water, you had food.

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:17.260 position:56%
And then there was-- telling that
the people in jail that they weren't

00:26:17.260 --> 00:26:19.970
that bad and that's something
I learn in the mountain.

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:23.890
I mean we're struggling
there, having horrible time,

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:25.870
we couldn't think that
we could be worst

00:26:25.870 --> 00:26:28.970
and then avalanche came
in and even more died.

00:26:28.970 --> 00:26:32.560
Then I learned that until you're
dead, you can always get worst

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:35.090
but you can always get better.

00:26:35.090 --> 00:26:37.700
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: And then
you went into politics.

00:26:37.700 --> 00:26:39.330
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa: Yeah.

00:26:39.330 --> 00:26:41.650
[ Laughter ]

00:26:41.650 --> 00:26:42.950
&gt;&gt; Ted Robbins: Porque?

00:26:42.950 --> 00:26:44.250
&gt;&gt; Roberto Canessa:
Well, because I said if--

00:26:44.250 --> 00:26:46.980
I said there are known politicians,

00:26:46.980 --> 00:26:51.240
they are [inaudible] well I put my
being known person at the service

00:26:51.240 --> 00:26:55.810
of politics and see if we can get a
place in the senate and everything.

00:26:55.810 --> 00:26:59.730 position:56%
So and the people were
complaining but why ask him to join.

00:26:59.730 --> 00:27:01.730
And they say, well, you
know, this is horrible.

00:27:01.730 --> 00:27:05.550
I'm a good friend of this
congressman and I cannot fail to--

00:27:05.550 --> 00:27:09.610
so I think the people's
speech is really perverted.

